## Key techniques used here

| Technique | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `@SpringBootTest` | Start the full application context with real beans. |
| `spring.autoconfigure.exclude=...` | Disable JPA/DataSource so no real DB is needed. |
| `@MockitoBean` (repository) | Replace only the data layer; keep everything above real. |
| `@AutoConfigureMockMvc` | Drive real HTTP requests through the whole chain. |
| `AtomicLong` in `willAnswer` | Simulate DB auto-increment ID generation. |
| `verify(repository)...` | Prove a call reached the data layer end-to-end. |

## Why all three test classes exist

These three classes form a deliberate **test pyramid**:
1. **`EmployeeServiceTest`** — many fast unit tests pin down business logic in isolation.
2. **`EmployeeControllerTest`** — slice tests verify HTTP/JSON/error mapping without business logic.
3. **`EmployeeIntegrationTest`** — fewer, slower tests prove the real beans wire and collaborate correctly.

A bug's location is narrowed by *which* layer's tests fail, and none of them require a running MySQL instance.
